On Consistent Bayesian Inference from Synthetic Data

\nameOssi Räisä \emailossi.raisa@helsinki.fi
\nameJoonas Jälkö \emailjoonas.jalko@helsinki.fi
\nameAntti Honkela \emailantti.honkela@helsinki.fi

Abstract

Generating synthetic data, with or without differential privacy, has attracted significant attention as a potential solution to the dilemma between making data easily available, and the privacy of data subjects. Several works have shown that consistency of downstream analyses from synthetic data, including accurate uncertainty estimation, requires accounting for the synthetic data generation. There are very few methods of doing so, most of them for frequentist analysis. In this paper, we study how to perform consistent Bayesian inference from synthetic data. We prove that mixing posterior samples obtained separately from multiple large synthetic data sets converges to the posterior of the downstream analysis under standard regularity conditions when the analyst’s model is compatible with the data provider’s model. We also present several examples showing how the theory works in practice, and showing how Bayesian inference can fail when the compatibility assumption is not met, or the synthetic data set is not significantly larger than the original.

Keywords: synthetic data, Bayesian inference, Bernstein-von Mises theorem, differential privacy

1 Introduction

Synthetic data has the potential of opening privacy-sensitive data sets for widespread analysis. The idea is to train a generative model with real data, and release synthetic data that has been generated from the model. The synthetic data does not contain records from real people, and ideally it preserves the population-level properties of the real data, making it useful for analysis. Privacy preservation can be guaranteed with differential privacy (DP) (Dwork et al., 2006b), which offers provable protection of privacy.

The most convenient and straightforward way for downstream analysts to analyse synthetic data is using the same method that would be used with real data. However, ignoring the additional stochasticity arising from the synthetic data generation will yield biased results and overconfident uncertainty estimates (Raghunathan et al., 2003; Wilde et al., 2021; Räisä et al., 2023). This is especially problematic under DP, which requires adding extra noise, which will be ignored if the synthetic data is treated like real data. This problem creates the need for noise-aware analyses that account for the synthetic data generation.

For frequentist downstream analyses, it is possible to account for the synthetic data generation by generating and analysing multiple synthetic data sets (Raghunathan et al., 2003). Recent work has extended this to DP synthetic data (Räisä et al., 2023), which allows generating multiple synthetic data sets without compromising on privacy. These methods reuse the analysis method for the real data, and only require using simple combining rules to combine the results from the analyses on each synthetic data set, making them simple to apply.

For Bayesian downstream analyses, Wilde et al. (2021) have shown that the analyst can use additional samples of public real data to correct their analysis. However, their method requires targeting a generalised notion of the posterior (Bissiri et al., 2016) and needs the additional public data for calibration. Ghalebikesabi et al. (2022) propose a correction using importance sampling to avoid the need of public data, but only prove convergence to a generalised posterior and do not clearly address the noise-awareness of the method.

The simple frequentist methods using multiple synthetic data sets were derived from methods in missing data imputation (Rubin, 1987), so our starting point is the method of Gelman et al. (2004, 2014) for Bayesian inference with missing data. They proposed inferring the downstream posterior by imputing multiple completed data sets, inferring the analysis posterior for each completed data set separately, and mixing the posteriors together. We investigate whether this method is also applicable to synthetic data, generated with or without DP.

1.1 Contributions

  1. 1.

    We study inferring the downstream analysis posterior by generating multiple synthetic data sets, inferring the analysis posterior for each synthetic data set as if it were the real data set, and mixing the posteriors together. We find two important conditions for consistent Bayesian inference with this method: synthetic data sets that are larger than the original one, and a notion of compatibility between the data provider’s and analyst’s models called congeniality (Meng, 1994).

  2. 2.

    We prove that when congeniality is met and the Bernstein–von Mises theorem applies, this method converges to the true posterior as the number of synthetic data sets and the size of the synthetic data sets grow. Under stronger assumptions, we prove a convergence rate for this method in the synthetic data set size, which we expect to match the rate that usually applies in the Bernstein–von Mises theorem (Hipp and Michel, 1976). These are presented in Section 3.

  3. 3.

    We evaluate this method with two examples in Sections 4 and 5: non-private univariate Gaussian mean or variance estimation, and DP Bayesian logistic regression. In the first example, we use the tractability of the model to derive further theoretical properties of the method, and in both examples, we verify that the method works in practice when the assumptions are met, and examine what can happen when they are not met. Our code is available under an open-source license111https://github.com/DPBayes/NAPSU-MQ-bayesian-downstream-experiments.

1.2 Related Work

Generating synthetic data to preserve privacy was, as far as we know, originally proposed by Liew et al. (1985). Rubin (1993) proposed accounting for the synthetic data generation in frequentist downstream analyses by adapting multiple imputation (Rubin, 1987), which involves generating multiple synthetic data sets, analysing each of them, and combining the results with so called Rubin’s rules (Raghunathan et al., 2003; Reiter, 2002). Recently, Räisä et al. (2023) have shown that multiple imputation also works for synthetic data generated under DP when the data generation algorithm is noise-aware in a certain sense.

Recently, van Breugel et al. (2023) have studied uncertainty quantification for prediction tasks when training on synthetic data. They propose generating multiple synthetic data sets, like the multiple imputation line of work, and experimentally show that aggregating predictions from the multiple synthetic data sets improves generalisation performance and uncertainty quantification. They use a similar Bayesian framework as we do to justify using multiple synthetic data sets, but their theoretical study of the framework is very light. In particular, they do not consider the effect of the synthetic data set size theoretically.

Wilde et al. (2021) study downstream Bayesian inference from DP synthetic data by considering the analyst’s model to be misspecified, and targeting a generalised notion of the posterior (Bissiri et al., 2016) to deal with the misspecification, which makes their method more difficult to apply than standard Bayesian inference. They also assume that the analyst has additional public data available to calibrate their method.

Ghalebikesabi et al. (2022) use importance sampling to correct for bias with DP synthetic data, and have Bayesian inference as an example application. However, they also target a generalised variant (Bissiri et al., 2016) of the posterior instead of the noise-aware posterior we target, and they do not evaluate uncertainty estimation, so the noise-awareness of their method is not clear.

We are not aware of any existing work adapting multiple imputation for Bayesian downstream analysis in the synthetic data setting. In the missing data setting without DP, where multiple imputation was originally developed (Rubin, 1987), Gelman et al. (2004, 2014) have proposed sampling the downstream posterior by mixing samples of the downstream posteriors from each of the multiple synthetic data sets. We find that this is not sufficient in the synthetic data setting, and add one extra component: our synthetic data sets are larger than the original data set. We compare the two cases in more detail in Section 3.5, and in particular explain why large synthetic data sets are not needed in the missing data setting.

Noise-aware DP Bayesian inference is critical for taking into account the DP noise in synthetic data, but only a few works address this even without synthetic data. Bernstein and Sheldon (2018) present an inference method for simple exponential family models. Their approach was extended to linear models (Bernstein and Sheldon, 2019) and generalised linear models (Kulkarni et al., 2021). Recently, Ju et al. (2022) developed an MCMC sampler that can sample the noise-aware posterior using a noisy summary statistic.

2 Background

In this section, we introduce some background needed for the rest of our work. We start by introducing Bayesian inference and the Bernstein–von Mises theorem in Section 2.1, and then introduce differential privacy in Section 2.2 and noise-aware synthetic data generation in Section 2.3.

2.1 Bayesian Inference

Bayesian inference is a paradigm of statistical inference where the data analyst’s uncertainty in a quantity Q𝑄Q after observing data X𝑋X is represented using the posterior distribution p​(Q|X)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋p(Q|X) (Gelman et al., 2014). The posterior is given by Bayes’ rule:

p​(Q|X)=p​(X|Q)​p​(Q)∫p​(X|Q′)​p​(Q′)​dQ′,𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋𝑝conditional𝑋𝑄𝑝𝑄𝑝conditional𝑋superscript𝑄′𝑝superscript𝑄′differential-dsuperscript𝑄′p(Q|X)=\frac{p(X|Q)p(Q)}{\int p(X|Q^{\prime})p(Q^{\prime})\,\mathrm{d}Q^{\prime}},

where p​(X|Q)𝑝conditional𝑋𝑄p(X|Q) is the likelihood of observing the data X𝑋X for a given value of Q𝑄Q, and p​(Q)𝑝𝑄p(Q) is the analyst’s prior of Q𝑄Q. Computing the denominator is typically intractable, so analysts often use numerical methods to sample p​(Q|X)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋p(Q|X) (Gelman et al., 2014).

It turns out that in many typical settings, the prior’s influence on the posterior vanishes when the data set X𝑋X is large. A basic example of this is the Bernstein–von Mises theorem (van der Vaart, 1998), which informally states that under some regularity conditions, the posterior approaches a Gaussian that does not depend on the prior as the size of the data set increases.

A crucial component of the theorem, and also our theory, is the notion of total variation distance which is used to measure the difference between two random variables or probability distributions. {definition}[] The total variation distance between random variables (or distributions) P1subscript𝑃1P_{1} and P2subscript𝑃2P_{2} is

where A𝐴A is any measurable set. As a slight abuse of notation, we allow the arguments of TV⁡(⋅,⋅)TV⋅⋅\operatorname{TV}(\cdot,\cdot) to be random variables, probability distributions, or probability density functions interchangeably. 2.2 Differential Privacy and Noise-Aware Synthetic Data

Differential privacy (DP) (Dwork et al., 2006b) quantifies the privacy loss from releasing the results of analysing data. The quantification is done by looking at the output distributions of the analysis algorithm for two data sets that differ in a single data subject (Dwork and Roth, 2014): {definition} An algorithm ℳℳ\mathcal{M} is (ϵ,δ)italic-ϵ𝛿(\epsilon,\delta)-DP if

Pr⁡(ℳ​(X)∈S)≤eϵ​Pr⁡(ℳ​(X′)∈S)+δPrℳ𝑋𝑆superscript𝑒italic-ϵPrℳsuperscript𝑋′𝑆𝛿\Pr(\mathcal{M}(X)\in S)\leq e^{\epsilon}\Pr(\mathcal{M}(X^{\prime})\in S)+\delta

for all measurable sets S𝑆S and all data sets X,X′𝑋superscript𝑋′X,X^{\prime} that differ in one data subject. The choice of ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon and δ𝛿\delta is a matter of policy (Dwork, 2008). One should set δ≪1/nmuch-less-than𝛿1𝑛\delta\ll\nicefrac{{1}}{{n}} for n𝑛n datapoints, as δ≈1/n𝛿1𝑛\delta\approx\nicefrac{{1}}{{n}} permits mechanisms that clearly violate privacy (Dwork and Roth, 2014).

A common primitive for making an algorithm DP is the Gaussian mechanism (Dwork et al., 2006a), which simply adds Gaussian noise to the output of a function: {definition} The Gaussian mechanism with noise variance σD​P2superscriptsubscript𝜎𝐷𝑃2\sigma_{DP}^{2} and function f𝑓f outputs f​(X)+𝒩​(0,σD​P2​I)𝑓𝑋𝒩0superscriptsubscript𝜎𝐷𝑃2𝐼f(X)+\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma_{DP}^{2}I) for input X𝑋X. For a given (ϵ,δ)italic-ϵ𝛿(\epsilon,\delta)-bound and function f𝑓f, the required value for σD​P2superscriptsubscript𝜎𝐷𝑃2\sigma_{DP}^{2} can be computed tightly using the analytical Gaussian mechanism (Balle and Wang, 2018).

2.3 Noise-Aware Private Synthetic Data

To solve the uncertainty estimation problem for frequentist analyses from DP synthetic data, Räisä et al. (2023) developed a noise-aware algorithm for generating synthetic data called NAPSU-MQ. NAPSU-MQ takes discrete data, summarises it with marginal queries, releases the query values under DP with the Gaussian mechanism, and finally generates multiple synthetic data sets. The downstream analysis is done on each synthetic data set, and the results are combined using Rubin’s rules for synthetic data (Raghunathan et al., 2003; Rubin, 1993), which use the multiple analysis results to account for the extra uncertainty coming from the synthetic data generation.

The synthetic data is generated by sampling the posterior predictive distribution

p​(X∗|s~)=∫p​(X∗|θ)​p​(θ|s~)​dθ,𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋~𝑠𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋𝜃𝑝conditional𝜃~𝑠differential-d𝜃p(X^{*}|\tilde{s})=\int p(X^{*}|\theta)p(\theta|\tilde{s})\,\mathrm{d}\theta, (1)

where θ𝜃\theta is the parameters of the synthetic data generator and s~~𝑠\tilde{s} is the noisy marginal query values. The conditioning on s~~𝑠\tilde{s} and including the Gaussian mechanism in the model is what makes NAPSU-MQ noise-aware, and allows Rubin’s rules to accurately account for the synthetic data generation and DP noise in the downstream analysis.

3 Bayesian Inference from Synthetic Data

When the downstream analysis is Bayesian, the analyst would ultimately want to obtain the posterior p​(Q|X,IA)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|X,I_{A}) of some quantity Q𝑄Q given real data X𝑋X, where IAsubscript𝐼𝐴I_{A} denotes the background knowledge such as priors of the analyst. We assume the analyst has a method to sample p​(Q|X,IA)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|X,I_{A}) if they had access to real data, and study what they can do when they only have access to synthetic data.

In the DP case, the exact posterior is unobtainable, so we assume that X𝑋X is only available through a noisy summary s~~𝑠\tilde{s} (Ju et al., 2022; Räisä et al., 2023), so the posterior is p​(Q|s~,IA)𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|\tilde{s},I_{A}). To unify these notations, we use Z𝑍Z to denote the observed values, so Z=X𝑍𝑋Z=X in the non-DP case, Z=s~𝑍~𝑠Z=\tilde{s} in the DP case, and the posterior of interest is p​(Q|Z,IA)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|Z,I_{A}). We summarise these random variables and their dependencies in Figure 1.

3.1 Congeniality

In the decomposition (2) of the analyst’s posterior, X∗superscript𝑋X^{*} should be sampled conditionally on the analyst’s background information IAsubscript𝐼𝐴I_{A}, while in reality the synthetic data provider could have different background information ISsubscript𝐼𝑆I_{S}.

A similar distinction has been studied in the context of missing data (Meng, 1994; Xie and Meng, 2016), where the imputer of missing data has a similar role as the synthetic data provider. Meng (1994) found that Rubin’s rules implicitly assume that the probability models of both parties are compatible in a certain sense, which Meng (1994) defined as congeniality.

As our examples with Gaussian distributions in Section 4 show, some notion of congeniality is also required in our setting. However, because we study synthetic data instead of imputation, and Bayesian instead of frequentist downstream analysis, we need a different formal definition. As the analyst only makes inferences on Q𝑄Q, it suffices that both the analyst and synthetic data provider make the same inferences of Q𝑄Q: {definition} The background information sets ISsubscript𝐼𝑆I_{S} and IAsubscript𝐼𝐴I_{A} are congenial for observation Z𝑍Z if

p​(Q|X∗,IS)=p​(Q|X∗,IA)𝑝conditional𝑄superscript𝑋subscript𝐼𝑆𝑝conditional𝑄superscript𝑋subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|X^{*},I_{S})=p(Q|X^{*},I_{A}) (4)

for all X∗superscript𝑋X^{*} and

p​(Q|Z,IS)=p​(Q|Z,IA).𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscript𝐼𝑆𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscript𝐼𝐴p(Q|Z,I_{S})=p(Q|Z,I_{A}). (5)

In the non-DP case, (5) is redundant, as it is implied by (4), but in the DP case, both are needed, as the parties may draw different conclusions on X𝑋X given Z=s~𝑍~𝑠Z=\tilde{s}.

Combining congeniality and (3),

∫p​(Q|X∗,IA)​p​(X∗|Z,IS)​dX∗=∫p​(Q|X∗,IS)​p​(X∗|Z,IS)​dX∗→p​(Q|Z,IS)=p​(Q|Z,IA),𝑝conditional𝑄superscript𝑋subscript𝐼𝐴𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋𝑍subscript𝐼𝑆differential-dsuperscript𝑋𝑝conditional𝑄superscript𝑋subscript𝐼𝑆𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋𝑍subscript𝐼𝑆differential-dsuperscript𝑋→𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscript𝐼𝑆𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscript𝐼𝐴\begin{split}\int p(Q|X^{*},I_{A})p(X^{*}|Z,I_{S})\,\mathrm{d}X^{*}&=\int p(Q|X^{*},I_{S})p(X^{*}|Z,I_{S})\,\mathrm{d}X^{*}\\ &\to p(Q|Z,I_{S})=p(Q|Z,I_{A}),\end{split} (6)

where the convergence is in total variation distance as the size of X∗superscript𝑋X^{*} grows. In the following, we assume congeniality, and drop IAsubscript𝐼𝐴I_{A} and ISsubscript𝐼𝑆I_{S} from our notation.

3.2 Consistency Proof

To recap, we want to prove that the posterior from synthetic data,

p¯n​(Q)=∫p​(Q|Xn∗)​p​(Xn∗|Z)​dXn∗,subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍differential-dsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q)=\int p(Q|X^{*}_{n})p(X^{*}_{n}|Z)\,\mathrm{d}X^{*}_{n}, (7)

converges in total variation distance to p​(Q|Z)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍p(Q|Z) as the size n𝑛n of Xn∗subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛X^{*}_{n} grows. We prove this in Theorem 3.2, which requires that both p​(Q|Z,Xn∗)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛p(Q|Z,X^{*}_{n}) and p​(Q|Xn∗)𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛p(Q|X^{*}_{n}) approach the same distribution as n𝑛n grows. We formally state this in Condition 3.2. In Lemma 3.2, we show that Condition 3.2 is a consequence of the Bernstein–von Mises theorem (Theorem 2.1) under some additional assumptions, so we expect it to hold in typical settings.

To make the notation more compact, let Q¯+n∼p​(Q|Z,Xn∗)similar-tosubscriptsuperscript¯𝑄𝑛𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛{\bar{Q}^{+}}_{n}\sim p(Q|Z,X^{*}_{n}), and let Q¯n∼p​(Q|Xn∗)similar-tosubscript¯𝑄𝑛𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛{\bar{Q}}_{n}\sim p(Q|X^{*}_{n}).

{condition}

as n→∞→𝑛n\to\infty, where the convergence in probability is over sampling Xn∗∼p​(Xn∗|Z,Q)similar-tosubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍𝑄X^{*}_{n}\sim p(X^{*}_{n}|Z,Q).

3.4 Finite Number of Synthetic Data Sets

We have now shown that the mixture of posteriors

p¯n​(Q)=∫p​(Q|Xn∗)​p​(Xn∗|Z)​dXn∗,subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍differential-dsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q)=\int p(Q|X^{*}_{n})p(X^{*}_{n}|Z)\,\mathrm{d}X^{*}_{n},

converges to the target posterior p​(Q|Z)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍p(Q|Z) as n𝑛n grows. However, sampling p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) exactly requires one synthetic data set per sample, which is not practical in realistic settings. We can further approximate by generating a fixed number m𝑚m of synthetic datasets and using a Monte-Carlo approximation of the integral:

p​(Q|Z)≈∫p​(Q|Xn∗)​p​(Xn∗|Z)​dXn∗≈1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xn∗=Xi,n∗),𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍differential-dsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛p(Q|Z)\approx\int p(Q|X^{*}_{n})p(X^{*}_{n}|Z)\,\mathrm{d}X^{*}_{n}\approx\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{n}=X^{*}_{i,n}), (8)

with Xi,n∗∼p​(Xn∗|Z)similar-tosubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍X^{*}_{i,n}\sim p(X^{*}_{n}|Z).

Total variation distance is a metric, so

TV⁡(1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xi,n∗),p​(Q|Z))≤TV⁡(1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xi,n∗),p¯n​(Q))+TV⁡(p¯n​(Q),p​(Q|Z)).TV1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍TV1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄TVsubscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍\begin{split}&\operatorname{TV}\left(\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{i,{n}}),p(Q|Z)\right)\leq\operatorname{TV}\left(\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{i,{n}}),{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q)\right)+\operatorname{TV}\left({\bar{p}}_{n}(Q),p(Q|Z)\right).\end{split}

Theorem 3.2 gives

limn→∞TV⁡(p¯n​(Q),p​(Q|Z))=0.subscript→𝑛TVsubscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍0\lim_{n\to\infty}\operatorname{TV}\left({\bar{p}}_{n}(Q),p(Q|Z)\right)=0.

If, for all n𝑛n, p​(Q|Xn∗)𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛p(Q|X^{*}_{n}) is continuous for all Xn∗subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛X^{*}_{n}, p​(Q|Xn∗)≤hn​(Xn∗)𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛subscriptℎ𝑛subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛p(Q|X^{*}_{n})\leq h_{n}(X^{*}_{n}) for an integrable function hn​(Xn∗)subscriptℎ𝑛subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛h_{n}(X^{*}_{n}), and 𝒬⊂ℝd𝒬superscriptℝ𝑑\mathcal{Q}\subset\mathbb{R}^{d} is compact, the uniform law of large numbers (Jennrich, 1969, Theorem 2) gives

supQ∈𝒬|1m∑i=1mp(Q|Xn∗=Xi,n∗)−p¯n(Q)|→0\sup_{Q\in\mathcal{Q}}\left|\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{n}=X^{*}_{i,n})-{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q)\right|\to 0 (9)

almost surely as m→∞→𝑚m\to\infty. If 𝒬=ℝd𝒬superscriptℝ𝑑\mathcal{Q}=\mathbb{R}^{d}, we can represent 𝒬𝒬\mathcal{Q} as a countable union of compact sets 𝒬ksubscript𝒬𝑘\mathcal{Q}_{k}, apply the uniform law of large numbers on each 𝒬ksubscript𝒬𝑘\mathcal{Q}_{k}, and use the union bound to obtain (9) for 𝒬𝒬\mathcal{Q}. A similar decomposition of 𝒬𝒬\mathcal{Q} can be done for many other constrained parameter sets encountered in practice.

This implies (van der Vaart, 1998, Corollary 2.30)

limm→∞TV⁡(1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xi,n∗),p¯n​(Q))=0subscript→𝑚TV1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄0\displaystyle\lim_{m\to\infty}\operatorname{TV}\left(\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{i,{n}}),{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q)\right)=0

for almost all Xi,n∗subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛X^{*}_{i,n}, so

limn→∞limm→∞TV⁡(1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xi,n∗),p​(Q|Z))=0subscript→𝑛subscript→𝑚TV1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍0\lim_{n\to\infty}\lim_{m\to\infty}\operatorname{TV}\left(\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{i,{n}}),p(Q|Z)\right)=0 (10)

almost surely when Xi,n∗∼p​(Xn∗|Z)similar-tosubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛𝑝conditionalsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑛𝑍X^{*}_{i,n}\sim p(X^{*}_{n}|Z).

In Figure 3, we see that the mixture of posteriors becomes very spiky with small m𝑚m and large n𝑛n, and does not fully converge to the target posterior when n𝑛n grows but m𝑚m is kept small. This suggests that

limm→∞limn→∞TV⁡(1m​∑i=1mp​(Q|Xi,n∗),p​(Q|Z))≠0subscript→𝑚subscript→𝑛TV1𝑚superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑚𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍0\lim_{m\to\infty}\lim_{n\to\infty}\operatorname{TV}\left(\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}p(Q|X^{*}_{i,{n}}),p(Q|Z)\right)\neq 0 (11)

because the distributions p​(Q|Xi,n∗)𝑝conditional𝑄subscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑖𝑛p(Q|X^{*}_{i,n}) become narrower as n𝑛n increases, so a fixed number of them is not enough to cover p​(Q|Z)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍p(Q|Z). This means that in practice, the number of synthetic data sets should be increased along with the size of the synthetic data sets.

3.5 Relation to Missing Data Imputation

Combining inferences by mixing posteriors from multiple data sets in the style of (2) was originally proposed by Gelman et al. (2004, 2014) for Bayesian inference with missing data, with completed data sets corresponding to synthetic data sets of our setting. Large completed data sets are not required in the missing data setting. We explain where this difference between the two settings arises next.

In the missing data setting, only a part Xo​b​ssubscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠X_{obs} of the complete data set X𝑋X is observed, while a part Xm​i​ssubscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠X_{mis} is missing (Rubin, 1987). To facilitate downstream analysis, the missing data are imputed by sampling Xm​i​s∼p​(Xm​i​s|Xo​b​s,II)similar-tosubscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠𝑝conditionalsubscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝐼𝐼X_{mis}\sim p(X_{mis}|X_{obs},I_{I}). Analogously with synthetic data, IIsubscript𝐼𝐼I_{I} represents the imputer’s background knowledge.

Like with synthetic data, we have the decomposition (Gelman et al., 2014)

p​(Q|Xo​b​s,IA)=∫p​(Q|Xo​b​s,Xm​i​s,IA)​p​(Xm​i​s|Xo​b​s,IA)​dXm​i​s.𝑝conditional𝑄subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝐼𝐴𝑝conditional𝑄subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠subscript𝐼𝐴𝑝conditionalsubscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝐼𝐴differential-dsubscript𝑋𝑚𝑖𝑠p(Q|X_{obs},I_{A})=\int p(Q|X_{obs},X_{mis},I_{A})p(X_{mis}|X_{obs},I_{A})\,\mathrm{d}X_{mis}. (12)

If the analyst’s and imputer’s models are congenial in the sense that

p​(Q|Xo​b​s,IA)=p​(Q|Xo​b​s,II)𝑝conditional𝑄subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝐼𝐴𝑝conditional𝑄subscript𝑋𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝐼𝐼p(Q|X_{obs},I_{A})=p(Q|X_{obs},I_{I})

and

4 Non-private Gaussian Examples

In this section, we look at the Bayesian inference of a univariate Gaussian mean or variance from mixing the posteriors from multiple synthetic data sets, which are also generated from the same model. This allows us to analytically examine various aspects of Bayesian inference from multiple synthetic data sets which are not visible in our high-level theory in Section 3, as all of the posteriors are analytically tractable and relatively simple. In particular, we find that the synthetic data set needs to be larger than the original data set (Section 4.3) and find a variance correction formula for the Gaussian setting that gets around this requirement (Section 4.4). We also look at two forms of uncongeniality, and find that they cause very different effects: estimating the mean with incorrect known variance converges to the data provider’s posterior, but estimating the variance with incorrect known mean does not converge to either party’s posterior. For reference, we list the posteriors for these Gaussian settings in Appendix A.3.

In the congenial case in the left panel of Figure 2, both parties have the same posterior given the real data X𝑋X, and the mixture of posteriors from synthetic data is very close to that. In the uncongenial case in the right panel, where the analyst underestimates the variance, the parties have different posteriors given X𝑋X, but the mixture of synthetic data posteriors is still close to the data provider’s posterior.

In Figure 3, we examine the convergence of the mixture of posteriors from synthetic data under congeniality. We see that setting nX∗=nXsubscript𝑛superscript𝑋subscript𝑛𝑋n_{X^{*}}=n_{X} is not enough, as the mixture of posteriors is significantly wider than the analyst’s posterior for all values of m𝑚m. We also see that m𝑚m must be sufficiently large, otherwise the method produces very jagged posteriors, for example the top right corner.

5 Differentially Private Logistic Regression

Our second example is logistic regression with DP synthetic data. We consider two settings used by Räisä et al. (2023) with frequentist logistic regression, and change the downstream task to Bayesian logistic regression.

Under DP, Z𝑍Z is a noisy summary s~~𝑠\tilde{s} of the real data. We need synthetic data sampled from the posterior predictive p​(X∗|s~)𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋~𝑠p(X^{*}|\tilde{s}), which is exactly what the NAPSU-MQ algorithm of Räisä et al. (2023) provides. In NAPSU-MQ, s~~𝑠\tilde{s} contains the values of user-selected marginal queries with added Gaussian noise. We used the open-source implementation of NAPSU-MQ222https://github.com/DPBayes/NAPSU-MQ-experiments by Räisä et al. (2023), and describe NAPSU-MQ in Section 2.2.

5.1 Toy Data Logistic Regression

The first logistic regression setting we consider uses a simple toy data set of three binary variables, with nX=2000subscript𝑛𝑋2000n_{X}=2000 samples. The first two variables are sampled with independent coinflips, and the third is sampled from logistic regression on the other two, with coefficients (1,0)10(1,0). The prior for the downstream logistic regression is 𝒩​(0,10​I)𝒩010𝐼\mathcal{N}(0,10I).

We generate synthetic data with the NAPSU-MQ algorithm (Räisä et al., 2023), instructing the algorithm to generate m𝑚m synthetic data sets of size nX∗subscript𝑛superscript𝑋n_{X^{*}}. For the privacy bounds, we vary ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon, and set δ=nX−2=2.5⋅10−7𝛿superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑋2⋅2.5superscript107\delta=n_{X}^{-2}=2.5\cdot 10^{-7}.

Because of the simplicity of this model, it is possible to use the exact posterior decomposition (2) as a baseline, by using p​(X|s~)𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠p(X|\tilde{s}) instead of p​(X∗|s~)𝑝conditionalsuperscript𝑋~𝑠p(X^{*}|\tilde{s}) to generate synthetic data. We give a detailed description of this process in Appendix C. We have also included the DP-GLM algorithm (Kulkarni et al., 2021) that does not use synthetic data, and the non-DP posterior from the real data as baselines. We obtained the code for DP-GLM from Kulkarni et al. (2021) upon request.

5.1.1 Hyperparameters

For NAPSU-MQ, we use the hyperparameters of Räisä et al. (2023), except we used NUTS (Hoffman and Gelman, 2014) with 200 warmup samples and 500 kept samples for ϵ∈{0.5,1}italic-ϵ0.51\epsilon\in\{0.5,1\}, and 1500 kept samples for ϵ=0.1italic-ϵ0.1\epsilon=0.1, as the posterior sampling algorithm. The NAPSU-MQ prior is 𝒩​(0,102​I)𝒩0superscript102𝐼\mathcal{N}(0,10^{2}I), and the marginal queries are the full set of 3-way marginals of all three variables.

The hyperparameters of DP-GLM are the L2subscript𝐿2L_{2}-norm upper bound R𝑅R for the covariates of the logistic regression, a coefficient norm upper bound s𝑠s, and the parameters of the posterior sampling algorithm DP-GLM uses. We set R=2𝑅2R=\sqrt{2} so that the covariates do not get clipped, and set s=5𝑠5s=5 after some preliminary runs. The posterior sampling algorithm is NUTS (Hoffman and Gelman, 2014) with 1000 warmup samples and 1000 kept samples from 4 parallel chains.

5.1.2 Results

Figure 7 compares the mixture of posteriors from synthetic data p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) from (7) that uses p​(Q|X∗)𝑝conditional𝑄superscript𝑋p(Q|X^{*}), with nX∗/nX=20subscript𝑛superscript𝑋subscript𝑛𝑋20n_{X^{*}}/n_{X}=20 and m=400𝑚400m=400 synthetic data sets, to the baselines. p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) is very close to the posterior p​(Q|s~)𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠p(Q|\tilde{s}) from (2). The DP-GLM posterior that does not use synthetic data is somewhat wider.

We ran the experiment 100 times and also with ϵ=0.1italic-ϵ0.1\epsilon=0.1 and ϵ=0.5italic-ϵ0.5\epsilon=0.5, and plot coverages and widths of credible intervals in Figure 8. With ϵ=1italic-ϵ1\epsilon=1 and ϵ=0.5italic-ϵ0.5\epsilon=0.5, the coverages are accurate and DP-GLM consistently produces wider intervals. With ϵ=0.1italic-ϵ0.1\epsilon=0.1, the mixture of synthetic data posteriors likely needs more and larger synthetic data sets to converge, as it produced wider and slightly overconfident intervals for one coefficient.

Figures 10 and 11 look at how p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) converges to p​(Q|s~)𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠p(Q|\tilde{s}) in terms of total variation distance as nX∗subscript𝑛superscript𝑋n_{X^{*}} and m𝑚m increase. They show that increasing both together decreases the total variation distance, but just increasing one leads to a plateau at some point.

5.1.3 Plotting Details

The plotted density of DP-GLM in Figure 7 is a kernel density estimate from the posterior samples DP-GLM returns. The non-DP density is a Laplace approximation. Both synthetic data methods use Laplace approximations in the downstream analysis, so their posteriors are mixtures of these Laplace approximations for each synthetic data set. This was also used in Figure 9.

5.2 UCI Adult Logistic Regression

To test our theory on real data, we used the UCI Adult data set (Kohavi and Becker, 1996) setting that was used to test NAPSU-MQ (Räisä et al., 2023). In this setting, the synthetic data set is generated from a subset of 10 columns333 age, workclass, education, marital-status, race, gender, capital-gain, capital-loss, hours-per-week and income , with the continuous columns age and hours-per-week discretised to 5 categories, and capital-loss and capital-gain binarised according to whether they are greater than 0 or not. The income column is already binarised in the original data to denote whether it is over $50000currency-dollar50000\$50000 or not. All rows with missing values in the original data set are deleted, which results in nX=46043subscript𝑛𝑋46043n_{X}=46043 datapoints. The downstream task is logistic regression predicting income using age, race and gender, with age converted back to a continuous value by picking the midpoint of each category. The reference value for race is “white” and for gender is “female”. These subsets were originally used to make the runtime of NAPSU-MQ manageable, and to make sure that enough relevant information for the downstream task can be included in the input queries for NAPSU-MQ (Räisä et al., 2023).

5.2.1 Algorithms and Hyperparameters

The target distribution p​(Q|Z)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑍p(Q|Z) is not tractable in this setting, so we used the non-DP Laplace approximation from the original data set, and the DP variational inference (DPVI) algorithm (Jälkö et al., 2017; Prediger et al., 2022) as baselines. We also tried running DP-GLM (Kulkarni et al., 2021), but we were not able to get useful results out of it in this setting. We have also included the Gaussian approximation to the mixture of synthetic data posteriors discussed in Section 4.4, which is called “with variance correction” in the figures.

The prior for the downstream Bayesian logistic regression is 𝒩​(0,10​I)𝒩010𝐼\mathcal{N}(0,10I), i.i.d. for each coefficient. The privacy parameters are ϵ∈{0.25,0.5,1}italic-ϵ0.250.51\epsilon\in\{0.25,0.5,1\}, and δ=n−2≈4.7⋅10−10𝛿superscript𝑛2⋅4.7superscript1010\delta=n^{-2}\approx 4.7\cdot 10^{-10}. We repeat the experiment 20 times.

The hyperparameters, prior, and selected queries for NAPSU-MQ are the same as in the original paper (Räisä et al., 2023). The synthetic data set size and number are nX∗/nX=10subscript𝑛superscript𝑋subscript𝑛𝑋10n_{X^{*}}/n_{X}=10, m=100𝑚100m=100.

DPVI runs DP-SGD (Rajkumar and Agarwal, 2012; Song et al., 2013; Abadi et al., 2016), specifically DP-Adam, under the hood, so it inherits the clip bound, learning rate, number of iterations, and subsampling (without replacement) ratio hyperparameters from DP-SGD. We tuned these with the Optuna library (Akiba et al., 2019), using the bounds [0.1,50]0.150[0.1,50] for the clip bound, [10−4,10−1]superscript104superscript101[10^{-4},10^{-1}] for the learning rate, [104,105]superscript104superscript105[10^{4},10^{5}] for the number of iterations and [0.001,1]0.0011[0.001,1] for the subsampling ratio. We used the distance of the DPVI posterior mean from the non-DP real data Laplace approximation as the optimisation criterion. We also tried using KL divergence, which gave hyperparameters that produced much wider posteriors. We used 100 trials for the tuning, and repeated it independently for all values of ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon. The privacy cost of the hyperparameter tuning is not reflected in the final results. As the variational posterior, we used a mean-field Gaussian.

5.2.2 Results

Figure 12 compares posteriors from one of the 20 runs with ϵ=1italic-ϵ1\epsilon=1. The mixture of synthetic data posteriors p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) is fairly close to the non-DP posterior from the real data set, with the exception of two coefficients. The Gaussian approximation to p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) from Section 4.4 is very close to p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q). The posteriors from DPVI are close to non-DP posterior, but for some coefficients, they are too narrow to overlap the non-DP posterior.

The logistic regression coefficients for which p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) does not work well correspond to the two races with the smallest number of people in the original data set. These posteriors are very wide due to the fact that NAPSU-MQ adds noise uniformly to all queries, which means that the queries with small values, corresponding to minority groups in the data, get relatively larger amounts of noise.

Figure 13 shows credible interval coverages from the Adult experiment, computed from 20 runs. p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) does not achieve perfect coverages, as some information is lost due to not running NAPSU-MQ with all marginal queries. The coverages are still much better than DPVI.

Figure 14 shows the widths of credible intervals from the same 20 runs. DPVI produces narrower posteriors than p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q), but the width of p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) posteriors drops as ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon increases, reflecting the reduced uncertainty from DP, which is not the case for DPVI.

In summary, while DPVI is able to find the posterior mean fairly well, it fails to accurately reflect the additional uncertainty from DP, making the posteriors overconfident, which would lead to spurious findings if applied in practice. In contrast, p¯n​(Q)subscript¯𝑝𝑛𝑄{\bar{p}}_{n}(Q) accounts for the DP noise very well, at the cost of producing very wide posteriors for the coefficients with a large amount of noise. Estimating uncertainty reliably is much more important than producing a narrow uncertainty estimate: a very wide posterior containing the correct value signals uncertainty, but a narrow posterior in the wrong place is confidently incorrect.

5.2.3 Plotting Details

The plotted densities for the non-DP posterior and the mixture of synthetic data posteriors use Laplace approximations like in the toy data experiment. The posterior from DPVI is a multivariate Gaussian, which is plotted as is.

6 Discussion

Synthetic data are often considered as a substitute for real data that are sensitive. Since the data generation process is based on having access to Z𝑍Z, one might ask why is the synthetic data needed in first place. Why cannot we simply perform the downstream posterior analysis directly using Z𝑍Z? Our analysis allows Z𝑍Z to be an arbitrary, even noisy, representation of the data, and it might be difficult for the analyst to place a model for such generative process for Q𝑄Q. In most applications, the analyst does have a model for Q𝑄Q arising from the data. Therefore using the synthetic data as a proxy for the Z𝑍Z allows the analyst to use existing models and inference methods to perform the analysis.

6.1 Limitations

A clear limitation of mixing posteriors from multiple synthetic data sets is the computational cost of analysing many large synthetic data sets. This may be substantial for more complex Bayesian downstream models, where even a single analysis can be computationally expensive. However, the separate analyses can be run in parallel. We also expect that the information gained from sampling the posteriors from a few synthetic data sets could be used to speed up sampling the others, for example by using importance sampling, as they likely won’t be too far from the sampled ones.

Under DP, we need noise-aware synthetic data generation, which limits the settings in which the method can currently be applied. However, if new noise-aware methods are developed in the future, the method can immediately be used with them.

Condition 3.2 limits the applicability of our theory to downstream analyses where the prior’s influence vanishes as the sample size grows. This does not always happen for some models, such as some infinite-dimensional models, models where the number of parameters increases with data set size, and models with a support that heavily depends on the parameters. The method also requires congeniality, which basically requires the analyst’s prior to be compatible with the data provider’s. Our Gaussian examples in Section 4 show that it is sometimes possible to recover useful inferences even without congeniality. This is not always the case, so an important direction for future research is separating these two cases, and finding out what can be done in the latter case.

6.2 Conclusion

We considered the problem of consistent Bayesian inference using multiple, potentially DP, synthetic data sets, and studied an inference method that mixes the posteriors from multiple large synthetic data sets while re-using existing analysis methods designed for real data. We proved, under congeniality and the general and well-understood regularity conditions of the Bernstein–von Mises theorem, that the method is asymptotically exact as the sizes of the synthetic data sets grow. We studied the method in two examples: non-private Gaussian mean or variance estimation and DP logistic regression. In the former, we were able to use the analytically tractable structure of the setting to derive additional properties of the method, in particular examining what can happen without congeniality. In both settings, we experimentally validated our theory, and showed that the method works in practice. When examining what can go wrong when our assumptions are not met, we found that the method can still give sensible results in some cases, but not all, showing that the method should be applied with care. This greatly expands the understanding of Bayesian inference from synthetic data, filling a major gap in the synthetic data analysis literature.

A randomised test is a function ϕ:𝒳→[0,1]:italic-ϕ→𝒳01\phi\colon\mathcal{X}\to[0,1]. The interepretation of ϕ​(X)italic-ϕ𝑋\phi(X) is the probability of rejecting some null hypothesis after observing data X𝑋X.

Appendix C Sampling the Exact Posterior in the Toy Data Experiment

In order to sample the exact posterior p​(Q|s~)𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠p(Q|\tilde{s}), we use another decomposition:

p​(Q|s~)=∫p​(Q|s~,X)​p​(X|s~)​dX=∫p​(Q|X)​p​(X|s~)​dX,𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠𝑋𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠differential-d𝑋𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠differential-d𝑋p(Q|\tilde{s})=\int p(Q|\tilde{s},X)p(X|\tilde{s})\,\mathrm{d}X=\int p(Q|X)p(X|\tilde{s})\,\mathrm{d}X, (21)

where p​(Q|s~,X)=p​(Q|X)𝑝conditional𝑄~𝑠𝑋𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋p(Q|\tilde{s},X)=p(Q|X) due to the independencies of the graphical model in Figure 1. It remains to sample p​(X|s~)𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠p(X|\tilde{s}). This is not tractable in general, but is possible in the toy data setting due to using the full set of 3-way marginals that covers all possible values of a datapoint, and the simplicity of the toy data.

We can decompose

p​(X|s~)=∫p​(s|s~)​p​(X|s)​dθ​dX=∫p​(X|s)​∫p​(s,θ|s~)​dθ​dX,𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠𝑝conditional𝑠~𝑠𝑝conditional𝑋𝑠differential-d𝜃differential-d𝑋𝑝conditional𝑋𝑠𝑝𝑠conditional𝜃~𝑠differential-d𝜃differential-d𝑋p(X|\tilde{s})=\int p(s|\tilde{s})p(X|s)\,\mathrm{d}\theta\,\mathrm{d}X=\int p(X|s)\int p(s,\theta|\tilde{s})\,\mathrm{d}\theta\,\mathrm{d}X,

so we can sample (s,θ)∼p​(s,θ|s)similar-to𝑠𝜃𝑝𝑠conditional𝜃𝑠(s,\theta)\sim p(s,\theta|s) and then sample X∼p​(X|s)similar-to𝑋𝑝conditional𝑋𝑠X\sim p(X|s) to obtain a sample from p​(X|s~)𝑝conditional𝑋~𝑠p(X|\tilde{s}). Due to the simplicity of the toy data setting, sampling both p​(s,θ|s)𝑝𝑠conditional𝜃𝑠p(s,\theta|s) and p​(X|s)𝑝conditional𝑋𝑠p(X|s) is possible.

NAPSU-MQ uses the following Bayesian inference problem:

θ𝜃\displaystyle\theta ∼Priorsimilar-toabsentPrior\displaystyle\sim\mathrm{Prior}
X𝑋\displaystyle X ∼MEDθnsimilar-toabsentsuperscriptsubscriptMED𝜃𝑛\displaystyle\sim\mathrm{MED}_{\theta}^{n}
s𝑠\displaystyle s =a​(X)absent𝑎𝑋\displaystyle=a(X)
s~~𝑠\displaystyle\tilde{s} ∼𝒩​(s,σD​P2),similar-toabsent𝒩𝑠superscriptsubscript𝜎𝐷𝑃2\displaystyle\sim\mathcal{N}(s,\sigma_{DP}^{2}),

where a𝑎a are the marginal queries, σD​P2superscriptsubscript𝜎𝐷𝑃2\sigma_{DP}^{2} is the noise variance of the Gaussian mechanism, and MEDθnsuperscriptsubscriptMED𝜃𝑛\mathrm{MED}_{\theta}^{n} is the maximum entropy distribution (Räisä et al., 2023) with point probability

p​(x)=exp⁡(θT​a​(x)−θ0​(θ)),𝑝𝑥superscript𝜃𝑇𝑎𝑥subscript𝜃0𝜃p(x)=\exp(\theta^{T}a(x)-\theta_{0}(\theta)),

where θ0subscript𝜃0\theta_{0} is the log-normalising constant.

In the toy data setting, a𝑎a is the full set of 3-way marginals for all of the 3 variables. In other words, a​(x)𝑎𝑥a(x) is the one-hot coding of x𝑥x, so s=a​(X)𝑠𝑎𝑋s=a(X) is a vector of counts of how many times each of the 8 possible values is repeated in X𝑋X. This means that sampling p​(X|s)𝑝conditional𝑋𝑠p(X|s) is simple:

  1. 1.

    For each possible value of a datapoint, find the corresponding count from s𝑠s, and repeat that datapoint according the that count.

  2. 2.

    Shuffle the datapoints to a random order.

As the downstream analysis p​(Q|X)𝑝conditional𝑄𝑋p(Q|X) doesn’t depend on the order of the datapoints, the second step is not actually needed.

To sample p​(s,θ|s~)𝑝𝑠conditional𝜃~𝑠p(s,\theta|\tilde{s}), we use a Metropolis-within-Gibbs sampler (Gilks et al., 1995) that sequentially updates s𝑠s and θ𝜃\theta while keeping the other fixed. The proposal for θ𝜃\theta is obtained from Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) (Duane et al., 1987; Neal, 2011). The proposal for s𝑠s is obtained by repeatedly choosing a random index in s𝑠s to increment and another to decrement. It is possible to obtain negative values in s𝑠s from this proposal, but those will always be rejected by the acceptance test, as the likelihood for them is 0.

To initialise the sampler, we pick an initial value for θ𝜃\theta from a Gaussian distribution, and pick the initial s𝑠s by rounding s~~𝑠\tilde{s} to integer values, changing the rounded values such that they sum to n𝑛n while ensuring that all values are non-negative.

The step size for the HMC we used is 0.05, and the number of steps is 20. In the s𝑠s proposal, we repeat the combination of an increment and a decrement 30 times. We take 20000 samples in total from 4 parallel chains, and drop the first 20% as warmup samples.

The method described in this section is similar to the noise-aware Bayesian inference method of Ju et al. (2022). The difference between the two is that Ju et al. (2022) use X𝑋X instead of s𝑠s as the auxiliary variable, and they sample the X𝑋X proposals from the model, changing one datapoint at a time. This makes their algorithm more generalisable.
